To assign a `React.CSSProperties` object to a classname in React, you can use the `style` prop. Here's an example:

```tsx
import React from 'react';
import { Button } from 'antd';
import styles from './styles.module.css'; // Import CSS Module

const MyComponent = () => {
  const customStyle: React.CSSProperties = {
    padding: '10px', // Your desired padding value
    // Add other style properties as needed
  };

  return (
    <>
      <Button className={styles.customButton} style={customStyle}>
        Custom Button with Padding
      </Button>
    </>
  );
};

export default MyComponent;
```

In this example, we create a `customStyle` object of type `React.CSSProperties` and assign the desired padding value. You can add other style properties if needed. 

Then, we assign the `className` from your CSS Module (`customButton` in this example) to the `Button` component, and pass the `customStyle` object to the `style` prop. This applies the CSS class and CSS properties to the button.

Remember to import your CSS Module file (`styles.module.css`) at the top of your component file.

With this implementation, the custom styles defined in the `React.CSSProperties` object will be applied to the button using the provided CSS Module class name.

In a CSS Module file, you cannot directly define `React.CSSProperties` since CSS Modules primarily focus on scoping CSS class names rather than defining inline styles. However, you can use regular CSS syntax to define styles within a CSS Module file. Here's an example of how you can define styles using CSS syntax within a CSS Module file:

```css
/* styles.module.css */
.myCustomClass {
  padding: 10px; /* Your desired padding value */
  /* Add other style properties as needed */
}

.myCustomClassSub {
  color: red;
  /* Add other style properties as needed */
}
```

In the example above, we've defined different class names (`myCustomClass` and `myCustomClassSub`) with their corresponding style properties. You can specify as many style properties as you need using regular CSS syntax.

